50. acutis: requiring keenness of intellect. — Naeviust see n. on 20. — Truculento Pseudolo: these plays of Plautus (lived from 254 to 184 B. e.) we still possess. The Truculentus is so named from one of the characters, a slave of savage disposition who is·whee· dled; the Pseudolus from a cheating slave. The latter name is com· monly supposed to be a transcription from a Greek word ψεύδνλοε, which however nowhere occurs3 and as the change from Greek ν to Latin o is not found before l, Corssen assumes ψεύδ-αλος as the origi· nal word. The form Pseudulus of the name is probably later than Pseudolus. Livium: Livius Andronicus», the founder of Latin literature (lived from about 285 to 204 Β. 0.), who translated the Odyssey, also many Greek tragedies.
